05566nam a22007335i 9780271077895DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710778957 a10.1515/97802710778952doi  a(DE-B1597)583942  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aF517 7aHIS0360202bisacsh04a9771 ade Lezay-Marnésia, Claude-François, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLetters Written from the Banks of the Ohio /cClaude-François de Lezay-Marnésia. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tEditor's Note and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tLetters Written from the Banks of the Ohio -- tEditor's Foreword -- tLetter to Monsieur Le Chevalier de Boufflers, Member of the French National Assembly: Marietta, November 15, 1790 -- tLetter to Monsieur Jacques-Henri Bernardin de Saint- Pierre: Fort Pitt, November 2, 1791 -- tLetter to My Eldest Son: Philadelphia, December 15, 1791 -- tAppendix -- tProspectus for the Colony on the Ohio and Scioto Rivers in America (1789) -- tTh e French on the Banks of the Scioto: Letter to an Immigrant to Kentucky (1790) -- tTh e Paris High Court on the Scioto (1790) -- tLetter Written by a Frenchman Immigrating to the Lands of the Scioto Company (1790) -- tNew Prospectus of the Scioto Company (1790) -- tModern Chivalry: Containing the Adventures of Captain John Farrago and Teague O'Regan, His Servant (1792) -- tLetter to Monsieur Audrain, Merchant in Pittsburgh (1800) -- tMy Memories: To My Children (1851) -- tChronology -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Proper Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFirst published in French in 1792, Letters Written from the Banks of the Ohio tells the fascinating story of French aristocrat Claude-François de Lezay-Marnésia and the utopia he attempted to create in what is now Ohio. Looking to build a perfect society based on what France might have become without the Revolution, Lezay-Marnésia bought more than twenty thousand acres of land along the banks of the Ohio River from the Scioto Company, which promised French aristocrats a fertile, conflict-free refuge. But hostilities between the U.S. Army and the Native American tribes who still lived on the land prevented the marquis from taking possession. Ruined and on the verge of madness, Lezay-Marnésia returned to France just as the Revolution was taking a more radical turn. He barely escaped the guillotine before dying a few years later in poverty and desperation.This edition of the Letters, introduced and edited by Benjamin Hoffmann and superbly translated by Alan J. Singerman, presents the work for the first time since the beginning of the nineteenth century-and the first time ever in English. The volume features a rich collection of supplementary documents, including texts by Lezay-Marnésia's son, Albert de Lezay-Marnésia, and the American novelist Hugh Henry Brackenridge. This fresh perspective on the young United States as it was represented in French literature casts new light on a captivating and tumultuous period in the history of two nations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFrenchxHistoryx18th centuryxOhio River Valley. 0aFrenchxHistoryy18th centuryxOhio River Valley. 0aFrenchzOhio River ValleyxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh1 aBrackenridge, Hugh Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClaude-François-Adrien marquis de, Lezay-Marnésia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffmann, Benj